# Self-Improvement Rules

These rules exist to prevent token waste, reduce loop iterations, and maintain context quality across sessions.

## Before Writing Any Code

1. **Read first, write second.** Always read the target file before editing it. Never guess existing content.
2. **Check for existing patterns.** Search the codebase before creating a new utility, component, or store slice.
3. **One concern per file.** If a component exceeds ~150 lines, split it. Sections that share no state do not belong in the same file.
4. **Confirm section IDs exist** before adding navbar anchor links — mismatched IDs are a common bug in this project.

## Token Efficiency Rules

- **Never re-read files you just read** in the same session unless you've edited them and need to verify.
- **Never explain what you're doing in code comments** — let the code speak; only add comments for non-obvious intent.
- **Avoid large rewrites of unchanged sections.** Use targeted `StrReplace` edits instead of full file rewrites.
- **Check the memory/ folder first** before asking the user for project context — it may already be documented.
- **Do not install packages without checking `package.json` first** — many packages are already listed.

## Linting & Quality

- Run `ReadLints` after every substantive edit to catch type errors early.
- Fix ALL TypeScript errors before completing a task — don't leave `any` types or unused imports.
- Never use `// @ts-ignore` — fix the root cause.

## Updating Memory

After significant structural changes, update the relevant `memory/*.md` file:

| Change | Update |
|--------|--------|
| New component added | `memory/architecture.md` |
| Color/font token change | `memory/design-tokens.md` |
| Brand/copy change | `memory/project-brief.md` |
| New dependency added | `memory/architecture.md` |

## Session Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- Don't re-explore the entire codebase at the start of each session — read `memory/` instead
- Don't create new components when editing existing ones would suffice
- Don't add `console.log` debug statements — use TypeScript types to enforce correctness
- Don't run `npm install` for packages already in `node_modules` — check first
